\title{psychdsish: Create and Validate 'psych-DS'-Inspired Project Structures}
\description{
\if{html}{\figure{logo.png}{options: style='float: right' alt='logo' width='120'}}

Creates a standardised R project skeleton that is loosely inspired by the 'psych-DS' data standard (\url{https://psych-ds.github.io/}) for psychological data, and checks whether an existing project follows the same conventions. The layout is not fully 'psych-DS' compliant -- most notably it drops the JSON metadata requirement -- hence 'psych-DS-ish'. Alongside the directory structure it generates Quarto templates, a README, a licence, and a '.gitignore' with sensible defaults, and adds extra conventions for reproducibility and common 'tidyverse' workflows. A validator function reports whether a project follows the conventions and, where it does not, how to fix it. See Hussey (2025) \doi{10.5281/zenodo.21441984} for the archived software record.
